  <p>
    Color rules ruby value. The most prized tones are saturated, slightly purplish to pure red (often called “pigeon blood”). Inclusions are common and expected; eye-clean rubies are rare. Cuts that maximize color — oval, cushion, and antique-inspired shapes — are popular for engagement rings.
  </p>

  <h2>Pros &amp; Cons of Ruby Engagement Rings</h2>
  <h3>Pros</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Iconic color:</strong> Red communicates passion and commitment at a glance.</li>
    <li><strong>Durable:</strong> Mohs 9 hardness makes ruby suitable for everyday wear.</li>
    <li><strong>Versatile styles:</strong> Looks stunning in classic solitaires, diamond halos, and vintage settings.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Cons</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Price sensitivity to color:</strong> Fine, saturated reds can be expensive.</li>
    <li><strong>Treatments:</strong> Heat treatment is common; ask your jeweler for disclosure and documentation.</li>
  </ul>

